        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Clarifications Needed\n\n**1. No specific system identified**\nYour question asks about \"stability constants\" but doesn't specify a **metal** or **ligand**. The NIST SRD-46 database contains stability constants for thousands of metal–ligand systems — could you tell me which metal(s) and ligand(s) you're interested in?\n\n**2. Temperature: 200 °C is uncommon**\nThe vast majority of stability constant measurements in SRD-46 are recorded at or near **25 °C** (298.15 K). Data at **200 °C** is extremely rare. I can search for whatever high-temperature data exists, but the results may be very limited.\n\n**3. Pressure is not a standard variable in SRD-46**\nSRD-46 catalogs equilibrium constants as a function of **temperature** and **ionic strength**, but does **not** typically include **pressure** as a recorded condition. Most aqueous-phase stability constant measurements are performed at ambient pressure (~1 bar). Pressure effects on aqueous equilibria are generally small unless you're dealing with:\n- Supercritical or near-critical water\n- Gas-phase species (e.g., CO₂ solubility)\n- Very high-pressure geochemical environments",
